Editorial Director, AnchorDesk<br>
<br>
Death and taxes aren't life's only inevitabilities after all. There's another: Miniaturization. Things just keep getting smaller, just as surely as people pass on and the IRS extracts its due. <br>
<br>
Latest example: Bell Labs has come up with a carbon transistor, created not on the manufacturing lines of a chip-fabricating facility, but inside the beakers of an organic chemistry lab. <br>
<br>
The Bell Labs organic transistor features a channel length (the distance between electrodes) of .001 to .002 microns, or 1 to 2 nanometers. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> That's about the size of single molecule.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> To give you an even better idea of just how much shrinkage that represents, consider today's Pentium 4 chips, which sport a channel length of .18 microns, or 180 nanometers. <br>
<br>
THIS TECHNOLOGY holds the potential for packing a &quot;chip&quot; with thousands of times more transistors than you'd now find in a silicon microprocessor. Or think of it this way: This could make computing devices thousands of times smaller, yet thousands of times more powerful. <br>
<br>
Of course, these carbon chips won't be available anytime soon. Bell Labs was, at this stage, simply demonstrating a proof of concept. <br>
<br>
What's more, the pressure isn't exactly on. Despite predictions that current chip technology would soon reach its limits, microprocessor engineers and researchers keep refining conventional materials and manufacturing methods to keep apace of Moore's Law, which posits a doubling of transistors per chip every 18 months. <br>
<br>
Nevertheless, it's at least fascinating to speculate on the possibilities when carbon chips do come of age in 10 years or so: microcomputers, micro-machines, and micro-robots capable of super-calculating powers or sophisticated human-like intelligences, yet small enough to occupy spaces and places too tiny for the eye to see. <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Sorry if I bored you guys, but NanoTech has always fascinated me and I thought you folks might find this interesting as well.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
