<br>
I was under the impression that current technology is pushing the size limit right now, in the sense that electric signals travel at the speed of light, and thus a computer <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> could</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> be as big as a building, or as small as a penny, and it made no difference, because the bottleneck was never the speed at which the signals travelled, but the speed at which other operations were peformed. But these days, everything else has gotten so fast, that the signal speed has become the bottleneck. There is no way to speed the signals up, so you have to move the components closer. <br>
<br>
I think the progress will come from other things, for a while now though. Conceptual changes in programming, or software behavior, and user interfaces. Making software customizable, and user friendly will become more and more important, because everybody is using computers now. <br>
<br>
The way they quote Moore's law is cool though. It sounds like the scientists are working their ass off to keep up the performance increases, cos they are afraid Mr. Moore is gonna come arrest them or something. <br>
<br>
